    <datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
      <subfield code="a">We study the evolution leading to (or regressing from) a large fluctuation in a statistical mechanical system. We introduce and study analytically a simple model of many identically and independently distributed microscopic variables nm (m=1,M) evolving by means of a master equation. We show that the process producing a nontypical fluctuation with a value of N=∑m=1Mnm well above the average 〈N〉 is slow. Such process is characterized by the power-law growth of the largest possible observable value of N at a given time t. We find similar features also for the reverse process of the regression from a rare state with N≫〈N〉 to a typical one with N≃〈N〉.</subfield>
      <subfield code="9">APS</subfield>
    </datafield>
